    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Forming inequalities from graphs is the <term>reverse process</term> of graphing inequalities. Given a shaded region on a coordinate plane, we must determine the algebraic inequality that produces that graph.
        </p>
        <p>
            The systematic process involves four major steps:
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Identify the boundary line:</term> Find two clear points on the edge of the shaded region to calculate the boundary equation using slope-intercept form (<m>y = mx + b</m>) or standard form (<m>Ax + By = C</m>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Determine the inequality symbol:</term> Check the line style. Solid lines signify inclusive constraints (<m>\le, \ge</m>), while dashed lines signify exclusive constraints (<m>\lt, \gt</m>).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Identify the region:</term> Shading above a non-vertical line relates to <m>y \gt</m> or <m>y \ge</m>. Shading below relates to <m>y \lt</m> or <m>y \le</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <term>Verify with a test point:</term> Substitute an ordered pair from inside the shaded area into your formula. It must yield a true statement.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Examine the coordinate plane graph below. Determine the algebraic inequality represented by this shaded region.
            </p>
            <p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw[gray!20, thin] (-2,-2) grid (6,5);
                            \fill[fill=blue!15, opacity=0.6] (-2,3) -- (6,-1) -- (6,-2) -- (-2,-2) -- cycle;
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (6,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-2) -- (0,5) node[above=4pt] {$y$};
                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-2,3) -- (6,-1);
                            \fill[black] (0,2) circle (2.5pt) node[above right, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,2)$};
                            \fill[black] (4,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5} {
                                \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                            }
                            \node at (-0.4,-0.4) [font=\small] {0};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the boundary equation using the identified intercepts <m>(0, 2)</m> and <m>(4, 0)</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m = \frac{0 - 2}{4 - 0} = -\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The slope-intercept form is <m>y = -\frac{1}{2}x + 2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The boundary line is drawn as a <term>solid line</term>, meaning we will use either <m>\le</m> or <m>\ge</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The shaded area lies <term>below</term> the boundary path. This implies a less-than constraint: <m>y \le -\frac{1}{2}x + 2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Test the point <m>(0,0)</m> which sits safely inside the shaded zone:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>0 \le -\frac{1}{2}(0) + 2 \implies 0 \le 2 \quad \text{(True)}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Converting to standard form by multiplying by 2 and moving variables left yields: <m>x + 2y \le 4</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Write down the linear inequality shown in the following dashed-boundary graph:
            </p>
            <p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % 1. Clean background grid
                            \draw[gray!20, thin] (-2,-5) grid (5,4);
                            
                            % 2. True infinite feasible region fill
                            \fill[fill=purple!15, opacity=0.6] (-1,-5) -- (3.5,4) -- (-2,4) -- (-2,-5) -- cycle;
                            
                            % 3. FIXED AXES: Extended bounds slightly past grid limits to prevent arrow clipping
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (5,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,4) node[above=4pt] {$y$};
                            
                            % 4. Dashed boundary line
                            \draw[dashed, thick, black] (-1,-5) -- (3.5,4);
                            
                            % 5. Intercept point markers
                            \fill[black] (0,-3) circle (2.5pt);
                            \fill[black] (1.5,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            
                            % 6. White-backed coordinate labels clear of grid lines
                            \node at (0,-3) [below right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,-3)$};
                            \node at (1.5,0) [above right=4pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(1.5,0)$};
                            
                            % 7. Ticks and grid numbering
                            \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {-4, -3, -2, -1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                            }
                            \node at (-0.4,-0.4) [font=\small] {0};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The graph displays a y-intercept at <m>b = -3</m> and crosses the line cleanly with a calculated slope of <m>m = 2</m>. The boundary line formula is:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>y = 2x - 3</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Because the boundary path is explicitly <term>dashed</term>, we use strict symbols: <m>\lt</m> or <m>\gt</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The shaded zone is situated <term>above</term> the sloped line. This points to a greater-than configuration: <m>y \gt 2x - 3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Verify with origin test point <m>(0,0)</m>:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>0 \gt 2(0) - 3 \implies 0 \gt -3 \quad \text{(True)}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rearranging into standard form gives the linear expression:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>y \gt 2x - 3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Which can also be expressed as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x - y \lt 3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A coordinate plane shows a shaded region. The boundary line passes through the points <m>(2, 0)</m> and <m>(0, -4)</m> and is drawn as a solid line. The shaded region is above the line. Write the inequality represented by this graph.
            </p>
            <p>
                <image>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % 1. Clean background grid
                            \draw[gray!20, thin] (-2,-5) grid (5,4);
                            
                            % 2. True infinite feasible region fill (above the line 2x - y = 4)
                            \fill[fill=purple!15, opacity=0.6] (-0.5,-5) -- (4,4) -- (-2,4) -- (-2,-5) -- cycle;
                            
                            % 3. FIXED AXES: Extended bounds past grid limits to prevent arrowhead clipping
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (5,0) node[right=4pt] {$x$};
                            \draw[black, thick, &lt;-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,4) node[above=4pt] {$y$};
                            
                            % 4. Solid boundary line
                            \draw[solid, thick, black] (-0.5,-5) -- (4,4);
                            
                            % 5. Intercept point markers
                            \fill[black] (2,0) circle (2.5pt);
                            \fill[black] (0,-4) circle (2.5pt);
                            
                            % 6. White-backed coordinate labels clear of grid lines
                            \node at (2,0) [above right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(2,0)$};
                            \node at (0,-4) [below right=2pt, font=\small, fill=white, inner sep=1pt] {$(0,-4)$};
                            
                            % 7. Ticks and grid numbering
                            \foreach \x in {-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} {
                                \draw (\x, 0.1) -- (\x, -0.1) node[below=3pt, font=\small] {$\x$};
                            }
                            \foreach \y in {-4, -3, -2, -1, 1, 2, 3} {
                                \draw (0.1, \y) -- (-0.1, \y) node[left=3pt, font=\small] {$\y$};
                            }
                            \node at (-0.4,-0.4) [font=\small] {0};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            First, we find the equation of the boundary line using the two points <m>(2, 0)</m> and <m>(0, -4)</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>m = \frac{-4 - 0}{0 - 2} = \frac{-4}{-2} = 2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Using point-slope form with the point <m>(0, -4)</m> (the y-intercept): <m>y = 2x - 4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since the boundary line is <term>solid</term>, we use <m>\le</m> or <m>\ge</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The shaded region is <term>above</term> the line, which means the <m>y</m>-values in the shaded region are greater than those on the line. This corresponds to the inequality: <m>y \ge 2x - 4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let's verify with a test point. The point <m>(0, 0)</m> is in the shaded region (above the line since the line passes through <m>(0, -4)</m>). Substituting:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>0 \ge 2(0) - 4 \implies 0 \ge -4 \quad \text{(True)}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the inequality is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>y \ge 2x - 4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Rearranging to standard form gives:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x - y \le 4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

